    "created_at": "2026-01-27T04:25:26Z",
    "updated_at": "2026-01-27T04:25:26Z",
    "body": "**Analysis**\n\nThis isn't a Starship bug; it's an encoding issue in VS Code's shell integration script (`shellIntegration.ps1`).\n\n**What's happening:**\n\n1. VS Code's shell integration reads Starship's `continuation_prompt` (which contains the Unicode bullet `∙` U+2219) and sends it to VS Code via an OSC 633 escape sequence\n2. The script uses `[Console]::Write()` which encodes output using `[Console]::OutputEncoding`\n3. On some Windows systems, this defaults to a legacy code page (e.g., CP850) instead of UTF-8\n4. The Unicode `∙` character gets corrupted during encoding, which breaks the OSC 633 sequence mid-stream\n5. xterm.js (VS Code's terminal) fails to parse the corrupted sequence and outputs the unparsed remainder (`\\x1b[0m`) as literal text\n\n**Why it only happens in VS Code:** Other terminals don't inject shell integration that reads and re-encodes the continuation prompt.\n\n**Workarounds:**\n\n1. **Add to your PowerShell profile** (`$PROFILE`):\n   ```powershell\n   [Console]::OutputEncoding = [System.Text.Encoding]::UTF8\n   ```\n\n2. **Or use a simpler continuation prompt** in `starship.toml`:\n   ```toml\n   continuation_prompt = '>> '\n   ```\n\n3. **Or disable VS Code shell integration:**\n   ```json\n   \"terminal.integrated.shellIntegration.enabled\": false\n   ```\n\n**Proper fix:** VS Code's `shellIntegration.ps1` should set `[Console]::OutputEncoding = [System.Text.Encoding]::UTF8` to ensure consistent encoding. I'll be filing an issue/PR with VS Code.",
    "author_association": "NONE",
